[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] The **WebUSB API** provides a way to expose non-standard Universal Serial Bus (USB) compatible devices services to the web, to make USB safer and easier to use.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] USB is the de-facto standard for wired peripherals.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] The USB devices that you connect to your computer are typically grouped into a number of device classes—such as keyboards, mice, video devices, and so on.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] These are supported using the operating system's class driver.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Many of these are also web accessible via the WebHID API.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] In addition to these standardized devices, there are a large number of devices that don't fit into any class.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] These need custom drivers, and are inaccessible from the web due to the native code required to take advantage of them.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Installing one of these devices often involves searching on a manufacturer's website for drivers and, should you wish to use the device on another computer, repeating the process again.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] WebUSB provides a way for these non-standardized USB device services to be exposed to the web.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] This means that hardware manufacturers will be able to provide a way for their device to be accessed from the web, without having to provide their own API.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] When connecting a new WebUSB-compatible device, the browser displays a notification providing a link to the manufacturer's website.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] On arriving at the site the browser prompts for permission to connect to the device, then the device is ready for use.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] No drivers need be downloaded and installed.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides attributes and methods for finding and connecting USB devices from a web page.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] The event type passed to `USB` `connect` or `disconnect` events when the user agent detects a new USB device has been connected to, or disconnected from the host.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides access to metadata about a paired USB device and methods for controlling it.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Represents the result from requesting a transfer of data from the USB device to the USB host.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Represents the result from requesting a transfer of data from the USB host to the USB device.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Represents the status of an individual packet from a request to transfer data from the USB device to the USB host over an isochronous endpoint.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Represents the status of an individual packet from a request to transfer data from the USB host to the USB device over an isochronous endpoint.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides information about a particular configuration of a USB device and the interfaces that it supports.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides information about an interface provided by the USB device.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides information about a particular configuration of an interface provided by the USB device.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] Provides information about an endpoint provided by the USB device.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] The following example demonstrates how to access a connected Arduino device using `USB.requestDevice()`, which has a vendorId of `0x2341`.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] You can find all connected devices with `USB.getDevices()`.
[src:web-usb/api-webusb-api] In the following example, with the Arduino device connected, product and manufacturer name are printed to the console.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A **device driver** is software that operates or controls a particular type of device that is attached to a computer.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A driver provides a software interface to hardware devices, enabling other software to access hardware functions without needing to know precise details about the hardware.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A driver communicates with the device through the computer bus or communications subsystem to which the hardware connects.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] When a calling program invokes a routine in the driver, the driver issues commands to the device (drives it).
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Once the device sends data back to the driver, the driver may invoke routines in the original calling program.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Drivers are hardware-dependent and operating-system-specific.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] They usually provide the interrupt handling required for any necessary asynchronous time-dependent hardware interface.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The main purpose of device drivers is to provide hardware abstraction by acting as a translator between a hardware device and the applications or operating systems that use it.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Programmers can write higher-level application code independently of whatever specific hardware the end-user is using.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] For example, a high-level application for interacting with a serial port may simply have two functions for *send data* and *receive data*.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] At a lower level, a device driver implementing these functions would communicate with the particular serial port controller installed on a user's computer.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The commands needed to control a 16550 UART are much different from the commands needed to control a USB-to-serial adapter, but each hardware-specific device driver abstracts these details into the same (or similar) software interface.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Writing a device driver requires an in-depth understanding of how the hardware and the software work for a given platform function.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Because drivers require low-level access to hardware functions in order to operate, drivers typically operate in a highly privileged environment and can cause system operational issues if something goes wrong.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] In contrast, misbehavior in most user-level software on modern operating systems can be stopped without greatly affecting the rest of the system.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Even drivers executing in user mode can crash a system if the device is erroneously programmed.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] These factors make it more difficult and dangerous to diagnose problems.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The task of writing drivers thus usually falls to software or computer engineers who work for hardware-development companies.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] This is because, as employees, they have better information than most outsiders about the design of the hardware.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Moreover, it was traditionally considered in the hardware manufacturer's interest to guarantee that their clients can use their hardware in an optimal way.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Typically, the hardware abstraction portion of the driver is written by the operating system vendor, while the lower-level physical device access portion is implemented by the device vendor.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] However, in recent years, non-vendors have written numerous device drivers for proprietary devices, mainly for use with free and open source operating systems.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] In such cases, it is important that the hardware manufacturer provide information on how the device communicates.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Although this information can instead be learned by reverse engineering, this is much more difficult with hardware than it is with software.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Windows uses a combination of driver and minidriver, where the full class/port driver is provided with the operating system, and miniclass/miniport drivers are developed by vendors and implement hardware- or function-specific subset of the full driver stack.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Miniport model is used by NDIS, WDM, WDDM, WaveRT, StorPort, WIA, and HID drivers; each of them uses device-specific APIs and still requires the developer to handle device management tasks.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Microsoft has attempted to reduce system instability due to poorly written device drivers by creating a new framework for driver development, called Windows Driver Frameworks (WDF).
[src:web-usb/device-driver] This includes User-Mode Driver Framework (UMDF) that encourages development of certain types of drivers—primarily those that implement a message-based protocol for communicating with their devices—as user-mode drivers.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] If such drivers malfunction, they do not cause system instability.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The Kernel-Mode Driver Framework (KMDF) model continues to allow development of kernel-mode device drivers but attempts to provide standard implementations of functions that are known to cause problems, including cancellation of I/O operations, power management, and plug-and-play device support.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Apple has an open-source framework for developing drivers on macOS, called I/O Kit.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] In Linux environments, programmers can build device drivers as parts of the kernel, separately as loadable modules, or as user-mode drivers for certain types of devices where kernel interfaces exist, such as for USB devices.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Makedev includes a list of the devices in Linux, including ttyS (terminal), lp (parallel port), hd (disk), loop, and sound (these include mixer, sequencer, dsp, and audio).
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Microsoft Windows .sys files and Linux .ko files can contain loadable device drivers.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The advantage of loadable device drivers is that they can be loaded only when necessary and then unloaded, thus saving kernel memory.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Depending on the operating system, device drivers may be permitted to run at various different privilege levels.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The choice of which level of privilege the drivers are in is largely decided by the type of kernel an operating system uses.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] An operating system that uses a monolithic kernel, such as the Linux kernel, will typically run device drivers with the same privilege as all other kernel objects.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] By contrast, a system designed around microkernel, such as Minix, will run drivers as processes independent from the kernel but that use drivers for essential input-output functions.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] On Windows NT, a system with a hybrid kernel, it is common for device drivers to run in either kernel-mode or user-mode.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The most common mechanism for segregating memory into various privilege levels is via protection rings.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The primary benefit of running a driver in user mode is improved stability, since a poorly written user-mode device driver cannot crash the system by overwriting kernel memory.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Because of the diversity of modern hardware and operating systems, drivers operate in many different environments.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] So choosing and installing the correct device drivers for the given hardware is often a key component of computer system configuration.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Virtual device drivers represent a particular variant of device drivers.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] They are used to emulate a hardware device, particularly in virtualization environments, for example, when a guest operating system is run on a Xen host.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Instead of enabling the guest operating system to dialog with hardware, virtual device drivers take the opposite role and emulate a piece of hardware, so that the guest operating system and its drivers running inside a virtual machine can have the illusion of accessing real hardware.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Attempts by the guest operating system to access the hardware are routed to the virtual device driver in the host operating system, e.g., function calls.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The virtual device driver can also send simulated processor-level events like interrupts into the virtual machine.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Virtual devices may also operate in a non-virtualized environment.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] For example, a virtual network adapter is used with a virtual private network, while a virtual disk device is used with iSCSI.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A good example for virtual device drivers can be Daemon Tools.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] There are several variants of virtual device drivers, such as VxDs, VLMs, and VDDs.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A device on the PCI bus or USB is identified by two IDs which consist of two bytes each.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The vendor ID identifies the vendor of the device.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] The device ID identifies a specific device from that manufacturer/vendor.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A PCI device often has an ID pair for the main chip of the device, and also a subsystem ID pair that identifies the vendor, which may be different from the chip manufacturer.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Computers often have many diverse and customized device drivers running in their operating system kernel, which often contain various bugs and vulnerabilities, making them a target for exploits.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A *Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver* (BYOVD) attacker installs any signed, old third-party driver with known vulnerabilities that allow malicious code to be inserted into the kernel.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] Drivers that may be vulnerable include those for WiFi and Bluetooth, gaming/graphics drivers, and drivers for printers.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] There is a lack of effective kernel vulnerability detection tools, especially for closed-source operating systems such as Microsoft Windows where the source code of the device drivers is mostly proprietary and not available to examine, and drivers often have many privileges.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] A group of security researchers considers the lack of isolation as one of the main factors undermining kernel security, and published an isolation framework to protect operating system kernels, primarily the monolithic Linux kernel whose drivers they say get ~80,000 commits per year.
[src:web-usb/device-driver] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:web-usb/device-driver] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Introduced in 1996, USB was originally designed to standardize the connection of peripherals to computers, replacing various interfaces such as serial ports, parallel ports, game ports, and Apple Desktop Bus (ADB) ports.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Early versions of USB became commonplace on a wide range of devices, such as keyboards, mice, cameras, printers, scanners, flash drives, smartphones, game consoles.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB has since evolved into a standard to replace virtually all common ports on computers, mobile devices, peripherals, power supplies, and various other small electronics.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In the latest standard, the USB-C connector replaces many types of connectors for power (up to 240 W), displays (e.g.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] DisplayPort, HDMI), and many other uses, as well as all previous USB connectors.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] As of 2024, USB consists of four generations of specifications: USB 1.*x*, USB 2.0, USB 3.*x*, and USB4.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Each specification sub-version supports different signaling rates from 1.5 and 12 Mbit/s half-duplex in USB 1.0/1.1 to 80 Gbit/s full-duplex in USB4 2.0.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB also provides power to peripheral devices; the latest versions of the standard extend the power delivery limits for battery charging and devices requiring up to 240 watts as defined in USB Power Delivery (USB-PD) Rev.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Over the years, USB(-PD) has been adopted as the standard power supply and charging format for many mobile devices, such as mobile phones, reducing the need for proprietary chargers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB was designed to standardize the connection of peripherals to personal computers, both to exchange data and to supply electric power.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] It has largely replaced interfaces such as serial ports and parallel ports and has become commonplace on various devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Peripherals connected via USB include computer keyboards and mice, video cameras, printers, portable media players, mobile (portable) digital telephones, disk drives, and network adapters.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB connectors have been increasingly replacing other types of charging cables for portable devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The Type-A and Type-B connectors came in Standard, Mini, and Micro sizes.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The standard format was the largest and was mainly used for desktop and larger peripheral equipment.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The Mini-USB connectors (Mini-A, Mini-B, Mini-AB) were introduced for mobile devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Still, they were quickly replaced by the thinner Micro-USB connectors (Micro-A, Micro-B, Micro-AB).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The Type-C connector, also known as USB-C, is not exclusive to USB, is the only current standard for USB, is required for USB4, and is required by other standards, including modern DisplayPort and Thunderbolt.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] It is reversible and can support various functionalities and protocols, including USB; some are mandatory, and many are optional, depending on the type of hardware: host, peripheral device, or hub.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB specifications provide backward compatibility, usually resulting in decreased signaling rates, maximal power offered, and other capabilities.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 1.1 specification replaces USB 1.0.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 2.0 specification is backward-compatible with USB 1.0/1.1.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 3.2 specification replaces USB 3.1 (and USB 3.0) while including the USB 2.0 specification.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB4 "functionally replaces" USB 3.2 while retaining the USB 2.0 bus operating in parallel.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 3.2 specification added a second lane to the *Enhanced SuperSpeed System* besides other enhancements so that the *SuperSpeedPlus USB* system part implements the *Gen 1×2*, *Gen 2×1,* and *Gen 2×2* operation modes.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] However, the *SuperSpeed USB* part of the system still implements the one-lane *Gen 1×1* operation mode.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Therefore, two-lane operations, namely *USB 3.2 Gen 1×**2***(10 Gbit/s) and *Gen 2×**2***(20 Gbit/s), are only possible with Full-Featured USB-C.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] As of 2023, they are somewhat rarely implemented; Intel, however, started to include them in its 11th-generation SoC processor models, but Apple never provided them.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] On the other hand, *USB 3.2 Gen 1(×1)* (5 Gbit/s) and *Gen 2(×1)* (10 Gbit/s) have been quite common for some years.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Each USB connection is made using two connectors: a *receptacle* and a *plug*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Backward compatibility given by USB 2.0 implementation.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The Universal Serial Bus was developed to simplify and improve the interface between personal computers and peripheral devices, such as cell phones, computer accessories, and monitors, when compared with previously existing standard or *ad hoc* proprietary interfaces.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] For a product developer, using USB requires the implementation of a complex protocol and implies an "intelligent" controller in the peripheral device.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Developers of USB devices intended for public sale generally must obtain a USB ID, which requires that they pay a fee to the USB Implementers Forum (USB-IF).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Developers of products that use the USB specification must sign an agreement with the USB-IF.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Use of the USB logos on the product requires annual fees and membership in the organization.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A group of seven companies began the development of USB in 1995: Compaq, DEC, IBM, Intel, Microsoft, NEC, and Nortel.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Concepts of the 1979 Atari SIO serial bus, of the 8-bit Atari computers, and the 1980 IEEE-488 derived Commodore bus, and Hewlett Packard's HP-IL bus pioneered this approach.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A consortium led by Apple, and containing Sony, Panasonic (Matsushita), LG, Toshiba, Hitachi, Cannon, Philips Electronics, Compaq, Thomson and Texas Instruments, would develop the concept further, from 1986, as the IEEE 1394 firewire standard and patent pool.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Decuir, originally of Atari, then Commodore, and a designer of the Atari SIO common bus, would work on the USB project for Microsoft, obtaining one of the related US patents; SIO was cited as prior art when defending USB against a patent troll.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Ajay Bhatt and his team worked on the standard at Intel; the first integrated circuits supporting USB were produced by Intel in 1995.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Released in January 1996, USB 1.0 specified signaling rates of 1.5 Mbit/s (*Low Bandwidth* or *Low Speed*) and 12 Mbit/s (*Full Speed*).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] It did not allow for extension cables, due to timing and power limitations.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Few USB devices made it to the market until USB 1.1 was released in August 1998.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 1.1 was the earliest revision that was widely adopted and led to what Microsoft designated the "Legacy-free PC".
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Neither USB 1.0 nor 1.1 specified a design for any connector smaller than the standard type A or type B.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Though many designs for a miniaturized type B connector appeared on many peripherals, conformity to the USB 1.*x* standard was hampered by treating peripherals that had miniature connectors as though they had a tethered connection (that is: no plug or receptacle at the peripheral end).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] There was no known miniature type A connector until USB 2.0 (revision 1.01) introduced one.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 2.0 was released in April 2000, adding a higher maximum signaling rate of 480 Mbit/s (maximum theoretical data throughput 53 MByte/s) named *High Speed* or *High Bandwidth*, in addition to the USB 1.*x* *Full Speed* signaling rate of 12 Mbit/s (maximum theoretical data throughput 1.2 MByte/s).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Modifications to the USB specification have been made via engineering change notices (ECNs).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 3.0 specification was released on 12 November 2008, with its management transferring from USB 3.0 Promoter Group to the USB Implementers Forum (USB-IF) and announced on 17 November 2008 at the SuperSpeed USB Developers Conference.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 3.0 adds a new architecture and protocol named *SuperSpeed*, with associated backward-compatible plugs, receptacles, and cables.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] SuperSpeed plugs and receptacles are identified with a distinct logo and blue inserts in standard format receptacles.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The SuperSpeed architecture provides for an operation mode at a rate of 5.0 Gbit/s, in addition to the three existing operation modes.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Its efficiency is dependent on a number of factors including physical symbol encoding and link-level overhead.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] At a 5 Gbit/s signaling rate with 8b/10b encoding, each byte needs 10 bits to transmit, so the raw throughput is 500 MB/s.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] When flow control, packet framing and protocol overhead are considered, it is realistic for about two-thirds of the raw throughput, or 330 MB/s to transmit to an application.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] SuperSpeed's architecture is full-duplex; all earlier implementations, USB 1.0-2.0, are half-duplex, arbitrated by the host.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Low-power and high-power devices remain operational with this standard, but devices implementing SuperSpeed can provide an increased current of between 150 mA and 900 mA, by discrete steps of 150 mA.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 3.0 also introduced the USB Attached SCSI Protocol (UASP), which provides generally faster transfer speeds than the BOT (Bulk-Only-Transfer) protocol.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 3.1 specification, released in July 2013.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The increased bandwidth is a result of two-lane operation over the additional wires included in all Full-Featured USB‑C Fabrics (all involved devices, hubs, cables and host).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Starting with the USB 3.2 specification, USB-IF introduced a new marketing related naming scheme.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] To help companies with the branding of the different operation modes, USB-IF recommended branding the 5, 10, and 20 Gbit/s capabilities as *SuperSpeed USB 5Gbps*, *SuperSpeed USB 10Gbps*, and *SuperSpeed USB 20Gbps*, respectively.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In 2023, they were replaced again, removing *"SuperSpeed"*, with *USB 5Gbps*, *USB 10Gbps*, and *USB 20Gbps*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The **USB4** specification (Version 1.0) was released on 29 August 2019.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] It is based on the Thunderbolt 3 protocol, defines 20 and 40 Gbit/s signalling rates over USB-C, and allows tunneling of USB 3.2, USB 2.0, PCIe and DisplayPort protocols; Thunderbolt 3 compatibility is optional for USB4 hosts/devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Because of the previous confusing naming schemes, USB-IF decided to change it once again.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] As of 2 September 2022, marketing names follow the syntax "USB *x*Gbps", where *x* is the signalling rate in Gbit/s.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Overview of the updated names and logos can be seen in the adjacent table.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The operation modes USB 3.2 Gen 2×2 and USB4 Gen 2×2 – or: USB 3.2 Gen 2×1 and USB4 Gen 2×1 – are not interchangeable or compatible; all participating controllers must operate with the same mode.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A USB system consists of a host with one or more downstream facing ports (DFP), and multiple peripherals, forming a tiered-star topology.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Additional USB hubs may be included, allowing up to five tiers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A USB host may have multiple controllers, each with one or more ports.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Up to 127 devices may be connected to a single host controller.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB devices are linked in series through hubs.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The hub built into the host controller is called the *root hub*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A USB device may consist of several logical sub-devices that are referred to as *device functions*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A *composite device* may provide several functions, for example, a webcam (video device function) with a built-in microphone (audio device function).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] An alternative to this is a *compound device,* in which the host assigns each logical device a distinct address and all logical devices connect to a built-in hub that connects to the physical USB cable.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB device communication is based on *pipes* (logical channels).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A pipe connects the host controller to a logical entity within a device, called an *endpoint*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Because pipes correspond to endpoints, the terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Each USB device can have up to 32 endpoints (16 *in* and 16 *out*), though it is rare to have so many.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Endpoints are defined and numbered by the device during initialization (the period after physical connection called *enumeration*) and so are relatively permanent, whereas pipes may be opened and closed.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] There are two types of pipe: stream and message.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] When a host starts a data transfer, it sends a TOKEN packet containing an endpoint specified with a tuple of *(device_address, endpoint_number)*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] If the transfer is from the host to the endpoint, the host sends an OUT packet (a specialization of a TOKEN packet) with the desired device address and endpoint number.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] If the data transfer is from the device to the host, the host sends an IN packet instead.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] If the destination endpoint is a uni-directional endpoint whose manufacturer's designated direction does not match the TOKEN packet (e.g. the manufacturer's designated direction is IN while the TOKEN packet is an OUT packet), the TOKEN packet is ignored.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Otherwise, it is accepted and the data transaction can start.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A bi-directional endpoint, on the other hand, accepts both IN and OUT packets.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Endpoints are grouped into *interfaces* and each interface is associated with a single device function.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] An exception to this is endpoint zero, which is used for device configuration and is not associated with any interface.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A single device function composed of independently controlled interfaces is called a *composite device*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A composite device only has a single device address because the host only assigns a device address to a function.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] When a USB device is first connected to a USB host, the USB device enumeration process is started.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The enumeration starts by sending a reset signal to the USB device.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The signaling rate of the USB device is determined during the reset signaling.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] After reset, the USB device's information is read by the host and the device is assigned a unique 7-bit address.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] If the device is supported by the host, the device drivers needed for communicating with the device are loaded and the device is set to a configured state.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] If the USB host is restarted, the enumeration process is repeated for all connected devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The host controller directs traffic flow to devices, so no USB device can transfer any data on the bus without an explicit request from the host controller.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In USB 2.0, the host controller polls the bus for traffic, usually in a round-robin fashion.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The throughput of each USB port is determined by the slower speed of either the USB port or the USB device connected to the port.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] High-speed USB 2.0 hubs contain devices called transaction translators that convert between high-speed USB 2.0 buses and full and low speed buses.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] There may be one translator per hub or per port.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Because there are two separate controllers in each USB 3.0 host, USB 3.0 devices transmit and receive at USB 3.0 signaling rates regardless of USB 2.0 or earlier devices connected to that host.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Operating signaling rates for earlier devices are set in the legacy manner.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The functionality of a USB device is defined by a class code sent to a USB host.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] This allows the host to load software modules for the device and to support new devices from different manufacturers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB mass storage device class (MSC or UMS) standardizes connections to storage devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] At first intended for magnetic and optical drives, it has been extended to support flash drives and SD card readers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The ability to boot a write-locked SD card with a USB adapter is particularly advantageous for maintaining the integrity and non-corruptible, pristine state of the booting medium.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Though most personal computers since early 2005 can boot from USB mass storage devices, USB is not intended as a primary bus for a computer's internal storage.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] However, USB has the advantage of allowing hot-swapping, making it useful for mobile peripherals, including drives of various kinds.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Several manufacturers offer external portable USB hard disk drives, or empty enclosures for disk drives.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] These offer performance comparable to internal drives, limited by the number and types of attached USB devices, and by the upper limit of the USB interface.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Other competing standards for external drive connectivity include eSATA, ExpressCard, FireWire (IEEE 1394), and most recently Thunderbolt.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Another use for USB mass storage devices is the portable execution of software applications (such as web browsers and VoIP clients) with no need to install them on the host computer.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Media Transfer Protocol (MTP) was designed by Microsoft to give higher-level access to a device's filesystem than USB mass storage, at the level of files rather than disk blocks.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] MTP was designed for use with portable media players, but it has since been adopted as the primary storage access protocol of the Android operating system from the version 4.1 Jelly Bean as well as Windows Phone 8 (Windows Phone 7 devices had used the Zune protocol—an evolution of MTP).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The primary reason for this is that MTP does not require exclusive access to the storage device the way UMS does, alleviating potential problems should an Android program request the storage while it is attached to a computer.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The main drawback is that MTP is not as well supported outside of Windows operating systems.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A USB mouse or keyboard can usually be used with older computers that have PS/2 ports with the aid of a small USB-to-PS/2 adapter.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] For mice and keyboards with dual-protocol support, a passive adapter that contains no logic circuitry may be used: the USB hardware in the keyboard or mouse is designed to detect whether it is connected to a USB or PS/2 port, and communicate using the appropriate protocol.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Active converters that connect USB keyboards and mice (usually one of each) to PS/2 ports also exist.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] DFU is sometimes used as a flash memory programming protocol in microcontrollers with built-in USB bootloader functionality.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Examples of devices can using DFU include iPod and iPhone.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB Device Working Group has laid out specifications for audio streaming, and specific standards have been developed and implemented for audio class uses, such as microphones, speakers, headsets, telephones, musical instruments, etc.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The working group has published four versions of audio device specifications: USB Audio 1.0, 2.0, 3.0 and 4.0, referred to as "USB Audio Class" (UAC) or "Audio Device Class" (ADC).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] UAC 3.0 primarily introduces improvements for portable devices, such as reduced power usage by bursting the data and staying in low power mode more often, and power domains for different components of the device, allowing them to be shut down when not in use.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] UAC 2.0 introduced support for High Speed USB (in addition to Full Speed), allowing greater bandwidth for multi-channel interfaces, higher sample rates, lower inherent latency, and 8× improvement in timing resolution in synchronous and adaptive modes.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] UAC 1.0 devices are still common, however, due to their cross-platform driverless compatibility, and also partly due to Microsoft's failure to implement UAC 2.0 for over a decade after its publication, having finally added support to Windows 10 through the Creators Update on 20 March 2017.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] UAC 2.0 is also supported by macOS, iOS, and Linux, however Android only implements a subset of the UAC 1.0 specification.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] While the USB spec originally described asynchronous mode being used in "low cost speakers" and adaptive mode in "high-end digital speakers", the opposite perception exists in the hi-fi world, where asynchronous mode is advertised as a feature, and adaptive/synchronous modes have a bad reputation.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In reality, all types can be high-quality or low-quality, depending on the quality of their engineering and the application.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Asynchronous has the benefit of being untied from the computer's clock, but the disadvantage of requiring sample rate conversion when combining multiple sources.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The connectors the USB committee specifies support a number of USB's underlying goals, and reflect lessons learned from the many connectors the computer industry has used.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The female connector mounted on the host or device is called the *receptacle*, and the male connector attached to the cable is called the *plug*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The official USB specification documents also periodically define the term *male* to represent the plug, and *female* to represent the receptacle.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The design is intended to make it difficult to insert a USB plug into its receptacle incorrectly.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB specification requires that the cable plug and receptacle be marked so the user can recognize the proper orientation.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB cables and small USB devices are held in place by the gripping force from the receptacle, with no screws, clips, or thumb-turns as some connectors use.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The distinction of *A* and *B* connectors was to enforce the directionality inherent in USB: The single *host* has Type‑A receptacles and each *peripheral device* has a single Type‑B receptacle.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A *hub* provides multiple *downstream*-facing Type‑A receptacles and connects to the host through its single Type‑B receptacle (or a captive cable with a Type‑A plug).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A hub may connect to the host either directly or through one or more additional hubs.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Prior to Type‑C, USB On-The-Go allowed a device such as a smartphone to take either the *host* or the *peripheral device* role, with a single Type‑AB receptacle (Micro‑AB, superseded in 2014, or Mini-AB, deprecated 2007) that accepted both Type‑A and Type‑B plugs.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB connector types multiplied as the specification progressed.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The original USB specification detailed Standard‑A and Standard‑B plugs and receptacles.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] These were originally referred to as simply *Type‑A* and *Type‑B*; they were renamed *Standard* out of necessity to distinguish from Mini and later Micro connectors.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The data contacts in the Standard plugs are recessed compared to the power and ground contacts so that devices are safely electrically connected before the more delicate data communications circuitry is connected, preventing damage.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Some devices operate in different modes depending on whether the data connection is made.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Simple power sources do not include data connections, instead shorting the data contacts together, but allow any capable USB device to charge or operate through a standard USB cable.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Charging cables provide power connections but not data, though the standard requires at least a USB 2.0 data connection capability.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In a non-standard charge-only cable, the data wires are shorted at the device end; otherwise, the device may reject the charger as unsuitable.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 1.1 standard specifies that a standard cable can have a maximum length of 5 meters (16 ft 5 in) with devices operating at full speed (12 Mbit/s), and a maximum length of 3 meters (9 ft 10 in) with devices operating at low speed (1.5 Mbit/s).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB 2.0 provides for a maximum cable length of 5 meters (16 ft 5 in) for devices running at high speed (480 Mbit/s).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 3.0 standard does not directly specify a maximum cable length, requiring only that all cables meet an electrical specification: for copper cabling with AWG 26 wires the maximum practical length is 3 meters (9 ft 10 in).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Two computers (*hosts*) can easily be connected through a USB‑C cable, but before Type‑C hosts could not be connected to each other with common USB cables.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB bridge "cables", or data transfer cables, can be found within the market, offering direct PC to PC connections.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] A bridge "cable" is actually an electronic device that appears as a USB *peripheral device* to each of the connected *hosts*, allowing peer-to-peer communication between the computers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Such USB bridge cables are used to transfer files between two computers via their USB ports.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Popularized by Microsoft as Windows Easy Transfer, the Microsoft utility used a special USB bridge cable to transfer personal files and settings from a computer running an earlier version of Windows to a computer running a newer version.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In the context of the use of *Windows Easy Transfer* software, the bridge cable can sometimes be referenced as *Easy Transfer cable*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Many USB bridge / data transfer cables are still USB 2.0, but there are also a number of USB 3.0 transfer cables.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Despite USB 3.0 being ten times as fast as USB 2.0, USB 3.0 transfer cables are only two to three times as fast given their design.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] The USB 3.0 specification introduced an A-to-A cross-over cable without power for connecting two PCs.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] These are not meant for data transfer but are aimed at diagnostic uses.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB bridge cables have become less important with USB dual-role-device capabilities introduced with the USB 3.1 specification.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Under the most recent specifications, USB supports most scenarios connecting systems directly with a Type-C cable.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] For the capability to work, however, connected systems must support role-switching.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Dual-role capability requires there be *two* controllers within the system, as well as a *role controller*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] While this can be expected in a mobile platform such as a tablet or a phone, desktop PCs and laptops often do not support dual roles.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] USB host and hub recepticles supply power at a nominal 5 V DC via the V_BUS pin to upstreaming USB devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] This section describes the power distribution model of USB that existed before USB Power Delivery (USB-PD).
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] On devices that do not use BC or PD, USB provides up to 4.5 W through Type-A and Type-B connectors, and up to 15 W through USB-C.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] All pre-PD USB power is provided at 5 V.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] For a host providing power to devices, USB has a concept of the *unit load*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Any device may draw power of one unit, and devices may request more power in these discrete steps.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] It is not required that the host provide requested power, and a device may not draw more power than negotiated.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] To recognize Battery Charging mode, a dedicated charging port places a resistance not exceeding 200 Ω across the D+ and D− terminals.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] Shorted or near-shorted data lanes with less than 200 Ω of resistance across the D+ and D− terminals signify a dedicated charging port (DCP) with indefinite charging rates.
[src:web-usb/usb-p01] In addition to standard USB, there is a proprietary high-powered system known as PoweredUSB, developed in the 1990s, and mainly used in point-of-sale terminals such as cash registers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB signals are transmitted using differential signaling on twisted-pair data wires with 90 Ω ± 15% characteristic impedance.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB 2.0 and earlier specifications define a single pair in half-duplex (HDx).
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB4 Gen 4 requires the use of all four pairs but allow for asymmetrical pairs configuration.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] In this case one data wire pair is used for the upstream data and the other three for the downstream data or vice-versa.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB4 can use optional Reed–Solomon forward error correction (RS FEC).
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] In this mode, 12 × 16 B (128 bit) symbols are assembled together with 2 B (12 bit + 4 bit reserved) synchronization bits indicating the respective symbol types and 4 B of RS FEC to allow to correct up to 1 B of errors anywhere in the total 198 B block.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] A USB connection is always between an *A* end, a downstream-facing port (DFP) of either a *host* or a *hub*, and a *B* end, the upstream-facing port (UFP) of either a *peripheral device* or a *hub*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Historically, this was made clear by the fact that hosts had only Type-A and peripheral devices had only Type-B ports, and every compatible cable had one Type-A plug and one Type-B plug.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB-C (Type-C) is a single connector that replaces all legacy Type-A and Type-B connectors, so when both sides are equipment with USB Type-C ports, normally the device's type defines which is the DFP and which is the UFP.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Some devices, e.g. modern smart phones, can act as both.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Consequently, the connected devices negotiate which is the *host* and which is the *peripheral device*.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] During USB communication, data is transmitted as packets.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Initially, all packets are sent from the host via the root hub, and possibly more hubs, to devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Some of those packets direct a device to send some packets in reply.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The USB Implementers Forum introduced the Media Agnostic USB (MA-USB) v.1.0 wireless communication standard based on the USB protocol on 29 July 2015.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Wireless USB is a cable-replacement technology, and uses ultra-wideband wireless technology for data rates of up to 480 Mbit/s.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The USB-IF used WiGig Serial Extension v1.2 specification as its initial foundation for the MA-USB specification and is compliant with SuperSpeed USB (3.0 and 3.1) and Hi-Speed USB (USB 2.0).
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Devices that use MA-USB will be branded as "Powered by MA-USB", provided the product qualifies its certification program.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] InterChip USB is a chip-to-chip variant that eliminates the conventional transceivers found in normal USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The HSIC physical layer uses about 50% less power and 75% less board area compared to USB 2.0.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It is an alternative standard to SPI and I2C.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB-C (officially *USB Type-C*) is a standard that defines a new connector, and several new connection features.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Among them it supports *Alternate Mode*, which allows transporting other protocols via the USB-C connector and cable.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] This is commonly used to support the DisplayPort or HDMI protocols, which allows connecting a display, such as a computer monitor or television set, via USB-C.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] All other connectors are not capable of two-lane operations (Gen 1×2 and Gen 2×2) in USB 3.2, but can be used for one-lane operations (Gen 1×1 and Gen 2×1).
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] DisplayLink is a technology which allows multiple displays to be connected to a computer via USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It was introduced around 2006, and before the advent of Alternate Mode over USB-C it was the only way to connect displays via USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It is a proprietary technology, not standardized by the USB Implementers Forum and typically requires a separate device driver on the computer.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] At first, USB was considered a complement to FireWire (IEEE 1394) technology, which was designed as a high-bandwidth serial bus that efficiently interconnects peripherals such as disk drives, audio interfaces, and video equipment.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] In the initial design, USB operated at a far lower data rate and used less sophisticated hardware.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It was suitable for small peripherals such as keyboards and pointing devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] These and other differences reflect the differing design goals of the two buses: USB was designed for simplicity and low cost, while FireWire was designed for high performance, particularly in time-sensitive applications such as audio and video.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Although similar in theoretical maximum signaling rate, FireWire 400 is faster than USB 2.0 high-bandwidth in real-use, especially in high-bandwidth use such as external hard drives.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The newer FireWire 800 standard is twice as fast as FireWire 400 and faster than USB 2.0 high-bandwidth both theoretically and practically.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] However, FireWire's speed advantages rely on low-level techniques such as direct memory access (DMA), which in turn have created opportunities for security exploits such as the DMA attack.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The chipset and drivers used to implement USB and FireWire have a crucial impact on how much of the bandwidth prescribed by the specification is achieved in the real world, along with compatibility with peripherals.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The *IEEE 802.3af*, *802.3at*, and *802.3bt* Power over Ethernet (PoE) standards specify more elaborate power negotiation schemes than powered USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] *4PPoE*) over a cable up to 100 meters compared to USB 2.0, which provides 2.5 W with a maximum cable length of 5 meters.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] This has made PoE popular for Voice over IP telephones, security cameras, wireless access points, and other networked devices within buildings.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] However, USB is cheaper than PoE provided that the distance is short and power demand is low.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Ethernet standards require electrical isolation between the networked device (computer, phone, etc.) and the network cable up to 1500 V AC or 2250 V DC for 60 seconds.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB has no such requirement as it was designed for peripherals closely associated with a host computer, and in fact it connects the peripheral and host grounds.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] This gives Ethernet a significant safety advantage over USB with peripherals such as cable and DSL modems connected to external wiring that can assume hazardous voltages under certain fault conditions.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The *USB Device Class Definition for MIDI Devices* transmits Music Instrument Digital Interface (MIDI) music data over USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The MIDI capability is extended to allow up to sixteen simultaneous *virtual MIDI cables*, each of which can carry the usual MIDI sixteen channels and clocks.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB is competitive for low-cost and physically adjacent devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] However, Power over Ethernet and the MIDI plug standard have an advantage in high-end devices that may have long cables.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] USB can cause ground loop problems between equipment, because it connects ground references on both transceivers.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] By contrast, the MIDI plug standard and Ethernet have built-in isolation to 500V or more.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] The eSATA connector is a more robust SATA connector, intended for connection to external hard drives and SSDs. eSATA's transfer rate (up to 6 Gbit/s) is similar to that of USB 3.0 (up to 5 Gbit/s) and USB 3.1 (up to 10 Gbit/s).
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] A device connected by eSATA appears as an ordinary SATA device, giving both full performance and full compatibility associated with internal drives.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] eSATA does not supply power to external devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] This is an increasing disadvantage compared to USB.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Even though USB 3.0's 4.5 W is sometimes insufficient to power external hard drives, technology is advancing, and external drives gradually need less power, diminishing the eSATA advantage. eSATAp (power over eSATA, a.k.a.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] ESATA/USB) is a connector introduced in 2009 that supplies power to attached devices using a new, backward compatible, connector.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] On a notebook eSATAp usually supplies only 5 V to power a 2.5-inch HDD/SSD; on a desktop workstation it can additionally supply 12 V to power larger devices including 3.5-inch HDD/SSD and 5.25-inch optical drives.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] eSATAp support can be added to a desktop machine in the form of a bracket connecting the motherboard SATA, power, and USB resources.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] eSATA, like USB, supports hot plugging, although this might be limited by OS drivers and device firmware.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Thunderbolt combines PCI Express and DisplayPort into a new serial data interface.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Original Thunderbolt implementations have two channels, each with a transfer speed of 10 Gbit/s, resulting in an aggregate unidirectional bandwidth of 20 Gbit/s.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Thunderbolt 2 uses link aggregation to combine the two 10 Gbit/s channels into one bidirectional 20 Gbit/s channel.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Thunderbolt 3 and Thunderbolt 4 use USB-C.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Thunderbolt 3 has two physical 20 Gbit/s bi-directional channels, aggregated to appear as a single logical 40 Gbit/s bi-directional channel.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Thunderbolt 3 controllers can incorporate a USB 3.1 Gen 2 controller to provide compatibility with USB devices.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] They are also capable of providing DisplayPort Alternate Mode as well as DisplayPort over USB4 Fabric, making the function of a Thunderbolt 3 port a superset of that of a USB 3.1 Gen 2 port.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] DisplayPort Alternate Mode 2.0: USB4 (requiring USB-C) requires that hubs support DisplayPort 2.0 over a USB-C Alternate Mode.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] DisplayPort 2.0 can support 8K resolution at 60 Hz with HDR10 color.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] DisplayPort 2.0 can use up to 80 Gbit/s, which is double the amount available to USB data, because it sends all the data in one direction (to the monitor) and can thus use all eight data wires at once.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Various protocol converters are available that convert USB data signals to and from other communications standards.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Due to the USB standard's plug-and-play nature, host computers are vulnerable to USB devices containing malicious software.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It is possible to create a device that looks like a flash drive, but when plugged in, simulates a keyboard and types malicious commands.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] For example, on a computer running Microsoft Windows, the device can wait a set amount of time, then open PowerShell and download a malware script.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] Another malicious device is a USB killer, which sends high voltage pulses across the data lines, destroying or damaging whatever it is plugged into.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] In versions of Microsoft Windows before Windows XP, Windows would automatically run a script (if present) on certain devices via AutoRun, one of which are USB mass storage devices, which may contain malicious software.
[src:web-usb/usb-p02] It is possible to gain full system control by hacking a USB controller.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] The `USBConfiguration` interface of the WebUSB API provides information about a particular configuration of a USB device and the interfaces that it supports.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] Creates a new `USBConfiguration` object which contains information about the configuration on the provided `USBDevice` with the given configuration value.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] Returns the configuration value of this configuration.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] This is equal to the `bConfigurationValue` field of the configuration descriptor provided by the device defining this configuration.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] Returns the name provided by the device to describe this configuration.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] This is equal to the value of the string descriptor with the index provided in the `iConfiguration` field of the configuration descriptor defining this configuration.
[src:web-usb/usbconfiguration] Returns an array containing instances of the `USBInterface` describing each interface supported by this configuration.
